aspace_helpers.title: AC107.01-AC107.16 add containers to existing components

comments.body:
@phoebeno 
This is going to be a two-step process:
1. create the top_containers ("tc") in ASpace
2. link the top_containers to their respective archival objects ("ao")

Could you provide two separate spreadsheets to support those two processes please? 

For step 1, the data we need is:
- tc_type	
- tc_indicator	
- repo	
- barcode	
- ils_holding_id	
- location_uri	
- profile_uri
- restriction

For step 2, the data we need is:
- tc_barcode
- ao_uri

That should allow us to get the tc_uri for the new top_containers to link the two.

figgy.title: Cloud fixity failures for items no longer in Figgy

comments.body: It's resource: 5a110633-73ff-480e-ba19-bd9375ecbc51

In the past this has been because something's in Solr but not postgres. I grabbed the second page's JSON (https://figgy.princeton.edu/catalog.json?f%5Bmember_of_collection_titles_ssim%5D%5B%5D=Patron+Requests&page=2), parsed the IDs, and ran them through:

```
saved_ids = ChangeSetPersister.default.query_service.custom_queries.find_saved_ids(ids: ids)
irb(main):023:0> ids - saved_ids.map(&:to_s)
=> ["5a110633-73ff-480e-ba19-bd9375ecbc51"]
```

Checking the logs that got ingested earlier today. Looking to see if it was reingested, source metadata identifier is: 9952649933506421
d799c392-9bda-4157-93c6-6cf88cac6d6a was a reingest of the resource and seems to be working. I'll delete that record from solr.

I deleted the bad ID from Solr:

```
Blacklight.default_index.connection.delete_by_id("5a110633-73ff-480e-ba19-bd9375ecbc51")
Blacklight.default_index.connection.commit
```

I'm not sure how this sync issue happened. It was ingested at 3:52 on Monday, maybe some system event caused it?
Looks good now.
